EritSecurusI

Target IP: 10.10.222.191

Learn to exploit the BoltCMS software by researching exploit-db.

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application at port 80.


According to whatweb, it looks like the target is running Bolt CMS on port 80. The target is running nginx/1.6.2 web server and PHP 7.2.15.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application on port 80. Doing a directory search returns error codes as the target machine takes long time to respond.


Since this challenge provides me a link to a working RCE, I will use it against the target machine. The working exploit is shown above.

Exploitation


I downloaded the exploit on my machine and ran it against the target machine with the command python3 exp.py http://10.10.222.191 admin password. This landed me a simple shell. Time to upgrade this to a reverse shell connection. I tried to upgrade this simple shell to a reverse shell connection, but it did not work.


I overcame this by making a copy of the PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script on my machine and transferring it to the target machine via http-server. Then I changed the permission of this shell.php to be executable. Running pwd shows the reverse shell was downloaded at /var/www/html/public/files. I started a listener on port 80 on my machine and visited http://10.10.222.191/files/shell.php to start the reverse shell! Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as www-data, as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


Running find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null shows the interesting /var/www/html/app/database/bolt.db entry above. Is this a database of the web application?


Using sqlite3, I opened the database file. The content of this database is shown above. There are two users: admin and wileec. The password hash of both users are also shown above. There is an interesting IP address 192.168.100.1. Maybe I can pivot to this network?


I made a copy of the two password hashes on my machine and ran john against it. I obtained the passwords password and snickers.


I successfully escalated privileges horizontally from the user www-data to wileec using the password snickers, via su. After logging in, I notice this user has a private SSH key.


Using the command ssh wileec@192.168.100.1, I pivoted to this network. This user jsmith can execute the binary /usr/bin/zip with the help of sudo.


Using zip, I escalated my privileges to the user jsmith now.


This user jsmith can execute all commands. So I spawned a root shell with the command sudo bash. Now I have a root shell on the target machine.
